PROMPT 93: What are the inspection requirements for temporary support systems during bridge construction?
======================================================================
RESPONSE:
- Inspect and maintain temporary works in an acceptable condition.
- Perform an in-depth inspection of the temporary works in the presence of the CO no more than 24 hours before starting each concrete placement, or before allowing people to enter a coffe...- Discontinue concrete placement and take corrective action if settlement or deflections occur that deviate more than ⅜ inch from those shown on the approved drawings.
- Record settlement to the nearest ⅛ inch during concrete placement.
- Do not use the ground surface near falsework supports as a reference elevation.
- Provide tell-tales with surveyed measurements, or other acceptable means, for accurate measurement of falsework settlement.
- Clearly mark the capacity on each manufactured component according to FHWA-RD-93-033.- The Project Engineer shall see that the falsework and forms are constructed in accordance with the submitted plans.
- If it becomes necessary, or the Contractor desires to deviate from the submitted plans, a revised plan for review shall be submitted and the Contractor shall not start construction in accordance with the revised plan until the review is complete.
- All revisions to the plan shall be reviewed by the State Bridge and Structures Engineer (or Terminal Design Engineer) to ensure the structural integrity of the falsework and formwork.- Temporary bridges shall be designed to meet the requirement of BDM Section 10.13 and other BDM Sections as applicable.
- Bridges shall be configured to allow inspectors direct access to bearings, and access to within 3-feet of superstructure surfaces.
- See also Figure 2.3.11-1 for under-bridge-inspection-truck clearance requirements.
- Adequate clearance for maintenance and inspection of bearings shall be provided. The clearance shall be adequate to inspect, remove and replace the bearings.
- Jacking points shall be provided for bearing replacement. Jacking points shall be designed to support 200 percent of the calculated lifting load.
- Built-up plate girder bridges with girders 5-feet deep or greater in depth shall be detailed with safety handrails for inspectors walking the bottom flanges.
- At large gusset plate locations on truss bridges (3-feet wide or wider), cables or lanyard anchor...- The temporary bridge(s) shall be shown on the Bridge Preliminary Plan and shall include the minimum required length and minimum roadway width, including shoulders.
- The approaches to a temporary bridge, including but not limited to, slopes and reinforced slopes, shall be designed in accordance with Chapter 8 and the Geotechnical Design Manual.
- The Contractor shall maintain the temporary bridge, including the driving surface, throughout its service life.[[SRC_1]][[SRC_1]][[SRC_4]][[SRC_5]][[SRC_6]]

